<p><b>Tony Russell "Charles" Brown</b> (September 13, 1922 – January 21, 1999), born in <a href="/wiki/Texas_City,_Texas" title="Texas City, Texas">Texas City, Texas</a> was an American <a href="/wiki/Blues" title="Blues">blues</a> singer and pianist whose soft-toned, slow-paced blues-club style influenced the development of blues performance during the 1940s and 1950s. He had several hit recordings, including "<a href="/wiki/Driftin%27_Blues" title="Driftin' Blues">Driftin' Blues</a>" and "<a href="/wiki/Merry_Christmas_Baby" title="Merry Christmas Baby">Merry Christmas Baby</a>".<sup id="cite_ref-russell_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-russell-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p></p>
